description: From Middle English embossen, embosen, embocen, from Old French embocer, equivalent to em- +‎ boss (“a lump; bump; protuberance”).

verbs.description: emboss (third-person singular simple present embosses, present participle embossing, simple past and past participle embossed)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To mark or decorate with a raised design or symbol, extrude.
examples: The papers weren't official until the seal had been embossed on them.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To raise in relief from a surface, as an ornament, a head on a coin, etc.
examples: Then o'er the lofty gate his art emboss'd / Androgeo's death.

description: Perhaps from em- +‎ Old French bos, bois (“wood”). Compare imbosk.

verbs.description: emboss (third-person singular simple present embosses, present participle embossing, simple past and past participle embossed)

entries.meaning: (obsolete) Of a hunted animal: to take shelter in a wood or forest.
(obsolete) To drive (an animal) to extremity; to exhaust, to make foam at the mouth.
(obsolete) To hide or conceal in a thicket; to imbosk; to enclose, shelter, or shroud in a wood.
(obsolete) To surround; to ensheath; to immerse; to beset.
